<TEXT>
<P>
Rescuers cut through the wreckage of a twin-engine commuter plane high up a 
rugged Costa Rican mountain and retrieved all 23 bodies aboard, including those 
of five Americans, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed about 4,500 feet up 7,450-foot Pico Blanco Mountain, 10 miles 
southwest of San Jose, five minutes after taking off in a driving rainstorm 
Monday morning from the capital's airport. The State Department identified 
three of the Americans as David Ulland of Austin, Minn.; Lester Ross of 
Lancaster, Pa., and Norman Baltimore of East Smithfield, Pa. It said the 
families of two other Americans were being notified. 
