<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: HOLY LAWSUIT! ADAM WEST TAKES ON AD 
AGENCIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As Batman, television actor Adam West was accustomed to battling such villains 
as the Penguin and the Joker. But in Burbank Superior Court on Tuesday, West 
took on a more substantial foe -- a group of advertising agencies he alleges 
stole his characterization. 
</P>
<P>
West, who portrayed the caped crusader in the campy 1960s television series, is 
seeking $900,000 in damages from the agencies for producing a television 
commercial featuring another actor as Batman. West, 51, testified that the 
actor used gestures, mannerisms and speech patterns similar to ones he used in 
the series. 
</P>
<P>
The suit names three agencies -- Ian Leech &amp; Associates of Los Angeles, 
Ingalls, Quinn &amp; Johnson of Boston, and BBDO New York. Anthony Liebig, an 
attorney for the agencies, said they purchased the rights to portray Batman 
from DC Comics, which originated the character. 
</P>
<P>
"Actors perform roles, they don't own them," Liebig said. "If you want to do a 
commercial using Robin Hood, do you have to go deal with the estate of Errol 
Flynn?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
