<P>
TEXAS HIJACKING ATTEMPT FOILED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
AUSTIN, Tex. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A man claiming that he had a bomb tried to hijack a jetliner to Cuba but was 
overpowered by a police officer who sneaked up an escape chute after the plane 
made an emergency landing, authorities said today. 
</P>
<P>
No one was seriously hurt late Tuesday during the America West flight that was 
supposed to fly non-stop from Houston to Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 737 carrying 39 people landed in Austin shortly before midnight, 
after the pilot told the would-be hijacker that the plane needed to refuel, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
Passenger Robert Martin said the man had been sitting two rows in front of him, 
complaining loudly about American TV programs. 
</P>
<P>
Authorities identified the man as Jose Manuel Gonzalez-Gonzalez, a 39-year-old 
Cuban native who lives in New Orleans. FBI Agent Byron Sage said he expected 
the man to be charged with air piracy and kidnaping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
