</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BOSTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mayor Raymond Flynn and the media questioned each other about why the fatal 
stabbing of a white college student in a black neighborhood on Martin Luther 
King Jr.'s birthday took until today to make front-page headlines. 
</P>
<P>
Full accounts of the slaying were not published in Boston newspapers until this 
morning because police -- already under fire for their handling of the racially 
charged Carol Stuart murder investigation -- did not provide any details about 
the victim's identity until early Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Northeastern University sophomore Mark Belmore, 19, was returning from his 
girlfriend's dormitory around 12:25 a.m. Monday when he was attacked and 
stabbed 22 times barely a block from the campus, which borders the racially 
tense Roxbury neighborhood. Investigators were searching for four black 
teen-agers who witnesses said fled the scene. 
</P>
