<P>
HUNTS PUT MANSION UP FOR SALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DALLAS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 68-year-old mansion in fashionable Highland Park has been listed for sale by 
Caroline and Nelson Bunker Hunt, who emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy 
proceedings earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
The asking price on the six-bedroom, six-bath mansion overlooking Turtle Creek 
is $2.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
The house has marble fireplaces and a garden room with an Italian tile floor. 
</P>
<P>
Caroline Hunt said in a recent interview that her family intends to move into a 
smaller home. 
</P>
<P>
Because of the bankruptcy proceedings, the Hunts were forced to turn over 
holdings valued at more than $220 million. Hunt also had to give up his annual 
salary of $300,000 and income from widespread holdings, the Dallas Times Herald 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Because Texas law grants homeowners an unlimited exemption for a homestead in 
bankruptcy proceedings, the Hunts won't have to give any proceeds from the sale 
to creditors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
